1
00:01:50,213 --> 00:01:52,488
The essence of life isn't comic.

2
00:01:52,573 --> 00:01:54,450
lt's tragic.

3
00:01:54,533 --> 00:01:59,163
There's nothing intrinsically funny
about the terrible facts of human existence.

4
00:01:59,253 --> 00:02:04,771
l disagree. Philosophers call it absurd
because, in the end, all you can do is laugh.

5
00:02:04,853 --> 00:02:08,926
Human aspirations
are so ludicrous and irrational.

6
00:02:09,013 --> 00:02:12,767
l mean, if the underlying reality
of our being was tragic,

7
00:02:12,853 --> 00:02:15,413
my plays would make more than yours,

8
00:02:15,493 --> 00:02:19,452
because my stories would resonate
more profoundly with the human soul.

9
00:02:19,533 --> 00:02:25,369
l mean, it's exactly because tragedy
hits on the truly painful essence of life

10
00:02:25,453 --> 00:02:28,047
that people run to my comedies for escape.

11
00:02:28,133 --> 00:02:29,282
No, no.

12
00:02:29,373 --> 00:02:32,649
Tragedy confronts. Comedy escapes.

13
00:02:32,733 --> 00:02:35,327
Look, you guys,
what are we discussing here?

14
00:02:35,413 --> 00:02:41,329
ls there a deeper reality in comedy or
tragedy? Who can make such ajudgment?

15
00:02:41,413 --> 00:02:45,770
Look, let me tell you a story and you tell me,
is it material for a comedy or a tragedy?

16
00:02:45,853 --> 00:02:47,764
This happened to some people l know.

17
00:02:47,853 --> 00:02:51,641
lt's a small dinner party. The hosts
are trying to impress one of their guests.

18
00:02:51,733 --> 00:02:55,885
Suddenly the doorbell rings and out of
nowhere an unexpected person shows up.

19
00:02:55,973 --> 00:02:58,646
- A man or a woman?
- A woman. l'll give you the details

20
00:02:58,733 --> 00:03:01,122
and you tell me comedy or tragedy.

21
00:03:01,213 --> 00:03:05,206
So, the guest enters and
everyone is surprised, especially the host.

22
00:03:05,293 --> 00:03:08,012
Turns out she's got a particular problem...

23
00:03:08,093 --> 00:03:10,129
My God, that's quite amusing.

24
00:03:10,213 --> 00:03:13,922
l mean, she barges in unannounced
while they're eating.

25
00:03:14,013 --> 00:03:17,085
What you told us
would make a very good romantic comedy.

26
00:03:17,173 --> 00:03:21,291
- Because you see the world comically.
- You're missing the tragic implications.

27
00:03:21,373 --> 00:03:26,606
The entanglement it suggests.
No, l see the whole thing quite differently.

28
00:03:26,693 --> 00:03:29,127
l see this lone figure -

29
00:03:29,213 --> 00:03:32,330
a woman who's maybe just come off a bus.

30
00:03:32,413 --> 00:03:38,602
She's toting a suitcase. Maybe
she's searching nervously for an address.

31
00:04:02,133 --> 00:04:03,805
Hello?

32
00:04:03,893 --> 00:04:06,532
Who is it?

33
00:04:06,613 --> 00:04:07,807
Hello?

34
00:04:08,013 --> 00:04:09,605
Hello?

35
00:04:10,853 --> 00:04:13,890
- Can l help you, miss?
- The Springers.

36
00:04:13,973 --> 00:04:15,964
Top floor.

37
00:04:33,893 --> 00:04:37,681
- lt's really good.
- These speakers are wonderful.

38
00:04:37,773 --> 00:04:40,571
You do pick up
every little nuance of the orchestra.

39
00:04:40,653 --> 00:04:43,247
Tell me again
why l can't have a glass of wine?

40
00:04:43,333 --> 00:04:45,847
Every pregnancy,
she asks the same question.

41
00:04:45,933 --> 00:04:48,572
This is the ''Concerto in D''.

42
00:04:48,653 --> 00:04:51,486
Yes. My God,
you really know your Stravinsky.

43
00:04:51,573 --> 00:04:54,007
This would be good theme music for the play.

44
00:04:54,093 --> 00:04:56,448
- Lee?
- That's a brilliant idea.

45
00:04:56,533 --> 00:05:01,129
l need a little help with the final touches.

46
00:05:01,213 --> 00:05:05,604
- Can you get the two big serving dishes?
- l'm running out of obsequious banter.

47
00:05:05,693 --> 00:05:08,491
- How's it going?
- He thinks l'm perfect for the part.

48
00:05:08,573 --> 00:05:10,803
The goddamn producer
wants more of a name.

49
00:05:10,893 --> 00:05:16,092
l don't understand why they make
such a big deal. lt's not like it's the lead.

50
00:05:16,173 --> 00:05:19,529
My first audition went better.
l don't know what happened.

51
00:05:19,613 --> 00:05:23,208
- And l know it's not the lead, Laurel.
- Doesn't he have any clout?

52
00:05:23,293 --> 00:05:27,525
They want a name. l'm not a name.
You didn't marry a name.

53
00:05:27,973 --> 00:05:31,443
- Sally said how much she loves your place.
- How long are you here?

54
00:05:31,533 --> 00:05:34,923
Six months, and we're still not finished.

55
00:05:35,013 --> 00:05:37,732
We have to furnish slowly
cos we used up all our money.

56
00:05:37,813 --> 00:05:41,692
We could not go on in that one-bedroom.
The piano ate up the living room.

57
00:05:41,773 --> 00:05:46,051
We're living beyond our means. l get nervous.
Laurel is certain God will provide.

58
00:05:46,133 --> 00:05:49,489
- They're poor, but happy.
- Definitely poor.

59
00:05:49,573 --> 00:05:52,610
- What do you do, Peter?
- l'm a lawyer. No jokes, please.

60
00:05:52,693 --> 00:05:55,127
Think the music's a little too loud?

61
00:05:55,213 --> 00:05:59,286
l saw you listening to the Mahler and crying.
You should have seen her.

62
00:05:59,373 --> 00:06:03,127
She was listening to Mahler
with tears streaming down her face.

63
00:06:03,213 --> 00:06:05,886
She looked so beautiful. l wanted to hug her.

64
00:06:05,973 --> 00:06:09,329
Yeah. But l had to get up early
and film a deodorant commercial.

65
00:06:09,413 --> 00:06:12,610
That's work at least, right?

66
00:06:12,693 --> 00:06:14,923
l think someone rang before. Did you hear?

67
00:06:15,013 --> 00:06:19,291
- So, how do you all know each other?
- We grew up together, Cassie and l.

68
00:06:19,373 --> 00:06:23,161
We were those little girls at school
with the plaid skirts.

69
00:06:23,253 --> 00:06:27,724
- And Lee and l met at Northwestern.
- He was the star actor, the handsome athlete.

70
00:06:27,813 --> 00:06:31,283
Everybody wanted him. But Laurel got him.

71
00:06:34,773 --> 00:06:36,491
- Melinda?
- Hi.

72
00:06:36,573 --> 00:06:38,564
Melinda?

73
00:06:39,133 --> 00:06:41,886
- Hi, Melinda, hi.
- My goodness.

74
00:06:41,973 --> 00:06:43,770
God.

75
00:06:43,853 --> 00:06:45,252
Cassie.

76
00:06:45,333 --> 00:06:47,528
l'm stunned.

77
00:06:47,613 --> 00:06:49,569
Here, let me take these.

78
00:06:49,653 --> 00:06:52,087
God, look at you. You look so...

79
00:06:52,173 --> 00:06:55,131
No, don't. Don't say what you're thinking of.

80
00:06:55,213 --> 00:06:59,172
l've been on a bus.
l've been on a Greyhound bus since Tuesday,

81
00:06:59,253 --> 00:07:03,644
so l'm sure l look like
the wreck of the <i>Hesperus.</i>

82
00:07:03,733 --> 00:07:07,521
A bus from where?
l mean, what are you doing here?

83
00:07:07,613 --> 00:07:11,811
l've moved around.
l had to keep moving.

84
00:07:11,893 --> 00:07:14,407
Events unfolded

85
00:07:14,493 --> 00:07:17,883
in such a way that...

86
00:07:17,973 --> 00:07:20,248
ls it all right if l smoke?

87
00:07:20,333 --> 00:07:25,327
l just feel a little nervous
barging in on you like this.

88
00:07:25,413 --> 00:07:29,008
Why don't you sit down and eat with us?
This is Jack and Sally Oliver.

89
00:07:29,093 --> 00:07:30,128
- Hi.
- Hi.

90
00:07:30,213 --> 00:07:32,249
l'm Melinda Robicheaux.

91
00:07:32,333 --> 00:07:36,121
l've gone back to my mother's name.
lt's French. She was Parisienne.

92
00:07:36,213 --> 00:07:38,647
You must have dropped
off the goddamn moon.

93
00:07:38,733 --> 00:07:41,805
- Shall l get a chair?
- l could use a drink.

94
00:07:41,893 --> 00:07:44,123
Champagne or white wine.

95
00:07:44,213 --> 00:07:49,526
The truth is,
l've gotten very used to single malt Scotch.

96
00:07:49,613 --> 00:07:53,049
An acquaintance of mine
introduced me to it, so...

97
00:07:53,133 --> 00:07:56,330
l really should freshen up, though.

98
00:07:56,413 --> 00:08:00,008
lf l could just get a single malt Scotch, and...

99
00:08:00,093 --> 00:08:02,926
Look at me. Jesus. l need a hot shower.

100
00:08:03,013 --> 00:08:05,083
Yeah. OK, please...

101
00:08:05,173 --> 00:08:07,767
Excuse us. Please start.

102
00:08:07,853 --> 00:08:10,048
This is so unexpected.

103
00:08:12,053 --> 00:08:14,123
l'll say.

104
00:08:14,213 --> 00:08:18,365
- You had no hint she was coming?
- She was nuts then, and she's nuts now.

105
00:08:18,453 --> 00:08:21,525
- Did you see the look in her eyes?
- She's been on a bus.

106
00:08:21,613 --> 00:08:23,683
You were asking how we know each other.

107
00:08:23,773 --> 00:08:26,890
Melinda is the third musketeer.
We went to school together.

108
00:08:26,973 --> 00:08:31,046
- We haven't heard from her in ages.
- Yeah. She's had personal difficulties.

109
00:08:31,133 --> 00:08:35,524
She said she'd be coming to New York from...
l can't remember, Chicago or lndiana,

110
00:08:35,613 --> 00:08:39,765
and could we put her up?
Laurel said, ''Sure.'' l myself...

111
00:08:39,853 --> 00:08:44,165
This is not the time to discuss this.
Let's just eat and change the subject.

112
00:08:44,253 --> 00:08:49,008
Well, what can you do? We've all had friends
drop in unannounced. Remember your aunt?

113
00:08:49,093 --> 00:08:53,962
l put up an extra bed. l fix up the room for her.
She doesn't show when she says she will.

114
00:08:54,053 --> 00:08:57,807
So we try to contact her
and there's no trace of her.

115
00:08:57,893 --> 00:09:03,365
Two months later, she calls up unannounced
in the middle of a frigging dinner party.

116
00:09:03,453 --> 00:09:06,684
- Am l unreasonable?
- No, no!

117
00:09:07,013 --> 00:09:13,088
You're missing the whole point. You have the
makings of a delightful human comedy here.

118
00:09:13,173 --> 00:09:15,607
You missed the humour in everything.

119
00:09:15,693 --> 00:09:20,084
l see a sweet, tree-lined block
on the Upper East Side.

120
00:09:20,173 --> 00:09:25,645
lt's a dinner party. The husband is fawning
over his guest. He's a moviemaker.

121
00:09:25,733 --> 00:09:28,122
No, wait.

122
00:09:28,213 --> 00:09:34,686
Here's the idea. Make the film director the
wife. He's just her out-of-work actor husband.

123
00:09:34,773 --> 00:09:39,164
She's trying to impress the guest
and raise the money for an independent film.

124
00:09:39,253 --> 00:09:43,485
l just told Jennifer that Steve is interested
in investing in Susan's next movie.

125
00:09:43,573 --> 00:09:48,442
Yeah. l have most of the money. l've just
been trying to get it going now for two years.

126
00:09:48,533 --> 00:09:51,730
l liked your first picture.
Would you do this one on video too?

127
00:09:51,813 --> 00:09:55,089
No. That was just because
we only had $300,000.

128
00:09:55,173 --> 00:09:58,848
- This one will be on 35mm for sure.
- Well, how much do you need?

129
00:09:58,933 --> 00:10:02,369
l've raised about four million
and we need another two million.

130
00:10:02,453 --> 00:10:04,842
The problem is the theme is controversial.

131
00:10:04,933 --> 00:10:07,811
- What's the theme?
- Well, let's put it this way.

132
00:10:07,893 --> 00:10:13,968
lt's a mostly all-female cast
and it's called <i>The Castration Sonata.</i>

133
00:10:14,053 --> 00:10:17,648
- Do you happen to have single malt Scotch?
- You know, let me check.

134
00:10:18,333 --> 00:10:23,088
- Hurry. l'm running out of obsequious banter.
- Don't throw me. Everything's timed.

135
00:10:23,173 --> 00:10:26,643
Chilean sea bass and caramelised filo
is not like scrambled eggs.

136
00:10:26,733 --> 00:10:31,602
Well, he happens to love it. Does he love it
$2 million worth? God, l hope so.

137
00:10:31,693 --> 00:10:33,843
l told you we should keep single malt Scotch.

138
00:10:33,933 --> 00:10:35,651
- Who drinks it?
- He does.

139
00:10:35,733 --> 00:10:40,045
God, you're definitely going all out.
You're dressed very sexy.

140
00:10:40,133 --> 00:10:43,250
- Hobie, keep your eyes on the sea bass!
- OK, OK, OK.

141
00:10:43,813 --> 00:10:49,012
She goes down to buy
a bottle of single malt Scotch.

142
00:10:54,893 --> 00:10:56,884
Are you OK?

143
00:10:58,893 --> 00:11:01,248
Yeah, l'm fine.

144
00:11:01,333 --> 00:11:03,563
- Are you sure?
- Yeah.

145
00:11:07,813 --> 00:11:12,011
Here we go. These are
Coquilles St Jacques with cinnamon.

146
00:11:12,093 --> 00:11:17,451
And we're having sea bass in a caramelised
filo pastry, lightly dusted with lime powder.

147
00:11:17,533 --> 00:11:21,685
- Did someone send you a yuppie cookbook?
- Susan says you're a wonderful chef.

148
00:11:21,773 --> 00:11:24,492
l'm an out-of-work actor.

149
00:11:25,133 --> 00:11:27,124
Who's that?

150
00:11:28,413 --> 00:11:29,687
- Hi.
- Hi.

151
00:11:29,773 --> 00:11:32,162
l'm sorry. l hope l'm not intruding.

152
00:11:32,253 --> 00:11:34,608
No, it's OK.

153
00:11:36,533 --> 00:11:42,085
l've been having a kind of bad time
and l just took some sleeping pills.

154
00:11:42,173 --> 00:11:45,051
- Sleeping pills?
- How many?

155
00:11:45,133 --> 00:11:48,762
- 28.
- Whoa! Call 911.

156
00:11:48,853 --> 00:11:52,402
Stay and just eat. lt's gonna get cold.
Sit. Just stay and eat.

157
00:11:52,493 --> 00:11:54,051
lt's OK. lt's OK.

158
00:11:54,133 --> 00:11:56,727
- Hobie, make some black coffee.
- OK, OK.

159
00:11:56,813 --> 00:11:59,407
l'm allergic to coffee,
but do you have any vodka?

160
00:11:59,493 --> 00:12:02,132
- Vodka?
- Maybe we should call a doctor.

161
00:12:02,213 --> 00:12:05,205
lt's OK.
l just need something to calm my nerves.

162
00:12:05,293 --> 00:12:08,649
- Do you live in this building?
- l've been subletting for a month.

163
00:12:08,733 --> 00:12:11,372
- Somebody call a doctor.
- Careful.

164
00:12:11,453 --> 00:12:14,172
- l'm gonna be sick.
- That's the best thing.

165
00:12:14,253 --> 00:12:17,689
No, no, not on the carpet.
That's a new carpet. Go to the bathroom.

166
00:12:17,773 --> 00:12:20,492
l smell smoke. Can you smell smoke?

167
00:12:20,573 --> 00:12:24,202
God! The Chilean sea bass
lightly dusted with lime!

168
00:12:25,413 --> 00:12:30,487
Should you be taking those pills?
You didn't have any dinner.

169
00:12:31,773 --> 00:12:34,207
lf l don't, l can't sleep.

170
00:12:34,293 --> 00:12:38,081
Well, Cassie's put on weight,
not that l'd ever say anything to her.

171
00:12:38,173 --> 00:12:41,643
- Cassie's pregnant.
- Again?

172
00:12:41,733 --> 00:12:44,645
They swear they're stopping at three children.

173
00:12:44,733 --> 00:12:47,293
For me, two was just the right number.

174
00:12:47,373 --> 00:12:52,049
- ls there any word?
- No, there's none. There's nothing.

175
00:12:53,533 --> 00:12:57,811
Now, l don't want you to get panicky,
but l am planning on staying. Just for a while.

176
00:12:57,893 --> 00:13:03,445
l just need to find a place
and settle in and rebuild my career.

177
00:13:03,533 --> 00:13:06,445
And you did say that you had
enough room to put me up.

178
00:13:06,533 --> 00:13:09,969
We were surprised you never showed up.
We had everything ready.

179
00:13:10,053 --> 00:13:13,170
Lee had gotten your room in order.

180
00:13:13,253 --> 00:13:17,292
l apologise for that. l was going through
a kind of confused down period.

181
00:13:17,373 --> 00:13:21,366
l was worried. Lee couldn't figure out
how to get in contact with you.

182
00:13:21,453 --> 00:13:24,047
l'd no idea you were using different names.

183
00:13:24,133 --> 00:13:26,886
What happened?
l thought the worst was over.

184
00:13:27,893 --> 00:13:31,727
- Can l speak openly?
- Of course.

185
00:13:34,493 --> 00:13:37,087
l tried to commit suicide.

186
00:13:37,853 --> 00:13:40,287
You didn't.

187
00:13:40,373 --> 00:13:43,490
l did, and it wasn't a half-hearted attempt.

188
00:13:43,573 --> 00:13:45,882
lt wasn't a cry for help.

189
00:13:46,453 --> 00:13:51,447
Why? l thought everything that happened was
past. l thought you'd pulled yourself together.

190
00:13:51,533 --> 00:13:57,244
Because that's what l wrote you,
and some days l honestly thought it.

191
00:13:57,333 --> 00:14:02,248
But in the end,
l just couldn't take it any more.

192
00:14:02,693 --> 00:14:04,012
Melinda.

193
00:14:05,373 --> 00:14:09,048
You didn't find me because l was indisposed.

194
00:14:09,853 --> 00:14:15,246
lf you've never been in a state mental hospital
in a straitjacket, l wouldn't recommend one,

195
00:14:15,333 --> 00:14:18,928
especially not the one l was in,
in the Midwest.

196
00:14:19,013 --> 00:14:21,129
l'm overwhelmed.

197
00:14:21,213 --> 00:14:23,522
Are you OK? l mean...

198
00:14:23,973 --> 00:14:26,487
l'm all right. l'm on the road back.

199
00:14:26,573 --> 00:14:30,407
l'm still a little fragile
when everything closes in,

200
00:14:30,493 --> 00:14:33,769
but l get stronger every day.

201
00:14:33,853 --> 00:14:37,004
You know you're welcome to stay here
as long as you like.

202
00:14:41,333 --> 00:14:44,291
- There. How long is she gonna stay?
- Why?

203
00:14:44,373 --> 00:14:47,126
We promised my sister
could stay for Thanksgiving.

204
00:14:47,213 --> 00:14:50,728
- Well, Thanksgiving's not for a while.
- Well, l'm just saying.

205
00:14:50,813 --> 00:14:54,965
- She's trying to pull her life back together.
- She's her own worst enemy.

206
00:14:55,053 --> 00:14:58,204
- You don't know the details.
- Details? What details?

207
00:14:58,293 --> 00:15:01,012
She was married to some doctor.
She had two kids.

208
00:15:01,093 --> 00:15:04,051
What was she doing playing around with...
What was he?

209
00:15:04,133 --> 00:15:06,408
He was a photographer.

210
00:15:06,493 --> 00:15:07,687
Melinda.

211
00:15:07,773 --> 00:15:11,812
Lee's right. Whatever l went through,
l'm responsible for.

212
00:15:11,893 --> 00:15:15,647
Look, we've all been drinking
and we're really tired. lt's...

213
00:15:15,733 --> 00:15:18,042
No, he's right.

214
00:15:18,133 --> 00:15:22,809
l was married to a man who loved me
and gave me the two most beautiful children.

215
00:15:22,893 --> 00:15:26,772
That l'm not allowed
to set eyes on them is just proof

216
00:15:26,853 --> 00:15:29,731
of my weakness and my husband's strength.

217
00:15:29,813 --> 00:15:33,089
No. lt's disgusting how much influence
he had on the judge.

218
00:15:33,173 --> 00:15:35,733
lt's who you know. Life is all networking.

219
00:15:35,813 --> 00:15:40,443
l brought it on myself because l was bored.

220
00:15:41,413 --> 00:15:44,291
l mean, not bored with my children.

221
00:15:45,933 --> 00:15:48,401
God, they were the light of my life.

222
00:15:48,493 --> 00:15:52,088
But l was bored being a doctor's wife,

223
00:15:52,173 --> 00:15:55,529
just as my mother was bored
being a doctor's wife.

224
00:15:55,613 --> 00:16:01,404
Like Madame Bovary.
lt's not that St Louis isn't very beautiful.

225
00:16:01,493 --> 00:16:03,484
lt's just that

226
00:16:05,373 --> 00:16:11,767
everything that had seemed
so magical when l married Josh

227
00:16:11,853 --> 00:16:14,845
